New studies

EG 2022-2023 (1st prize)

File: Neuenschwander-2023-EG-1p.pgn

This study has a long history. It goes back to the year 1989, when I worked on a pawn ending with a reciprocal zugzwang position requiring the paradoxical move 1.a3! (instead of 1.a4) and allowing black to promote to a queen first.

About 8 years ago I took up the idea again but was unable to find the original version (which was, if I remember correctly, not particularly exciting despite the festina lente theme). So I had to start from scratch but was unable to find a decent realization, until last year. It was worth the wait as can be seen in the final version published in EG. The switch forth and back between queen and pawn endings adds a nice twist to the main theme of the study.

GBR: +4000.45f8h8 FEN: 5K1k/5pp1/4p3/5p2/3p3P/3P3Q/P3P3/6q1 w - - 0 1

1. Qf3 (1. Kxf7? Kh7 2. Kxe6 Qg6+ 3. Kd5 Qf7+ 4. Kxd4 Qa7+ 5. Kc3 Qa3+ 6. Kd2 Qxa2+ 7. Ke3 Qe6+ 8. Kf2 Qe5 9. Qg3 Qd4+ 10. Kg2 g6 with only a minimal advantage for White ) (1. h5? Qg5 = ) 1… Qg6 (1… Qg4 2. a4 +/-) 2. Qf4 (2. a4? e5 3. Qd5 Qf6) 2… Qf6 (2… f6 3. Qxd4 Qg4 4. Qd7 Qb4+ 5. Kf7 Qb8 (5… Kh7 6. Qc8) 6. a4 and White wins easily ) 3. Qg5 (3. Qd6? f4 4. a4 Qf5 5. Qxd4 e5 gives White only a minimal edge, for example, 6. Qc4 f3 7. exf3 Qxf3 8. Qe4 (8. a5 Qb7 9. Qa4 Qa6 10. Kxf7 Qf6+ 11. Ke8 Qe6+ 12. Kd8 Qd6+ 13. Qd7 (13. Kc8 Qxd3 14. a6 Qd5 15. a7 Qc5+ 16. Kb7 Qe7+ 17. Kb6 Qd8+ 18. Kc5 Qf8+ 19. Kc4 Qf7+ = perpetual check ) 13… Qc5 14. Qa4 Qd6+ 15. Qd7 Qc5 16. Qc7 Qf8+ 17. Kd7 Qf5+ 18. Kc6 Qxd3 19. Qxe5) ) 3… Qxg5 (3… e5 4. Qxf6 gxf6 5. a4) 4. hxg5 e5 5. a3!! ( After 5. a4? e4 6. a5 exd3 7. exd3 f4 8. a6 f3 9. a7 f2 10. a8=Q f1=Q , a position of mutual zugzwang arises, which Black holds with accurate play 11. Qb8 Qf2! 12. Qb7 Qh2! 13. Qc8 Kh7! 14. Qf5+ Kh8 15. Kxf7 Qc7+ = ) 5… e4 6. a4 exd3 (6… f4 7. a5 f3 8. exf3 e3 ( 8… exf3 leads to the main line ) 9. a6 e2 10. a7 e1=Q 11. a8=Q Qe6 (11… Kh7 12. Kxf7) 12. Qe4 Qd6+ 13. Kxf7 Qd7+ 14. Kf8 Qd6+ 15. Ke8 Qb8+ 16. Kf7 +/-) 7. exd3 f4 8. a5 f3 9. a6 f2 10. a7 f1=Q 11. a8=Q Now Black is in Zugzwang 11… Qf5 (11… Kh7 12. Qe4+ f5 13. gxf6+ Kh6 14. f7! +/-) 12. Qh1+ Qh7 13. Qxh7+ Kxh7 14. Kxf7 Kh8 15. Ke6 Kh7 16. Kf5! (final Zugzwang) (16. Ke5? Kg6 17. Kxd4 Kxg5 18. Ke5 Kg6 19. Ke6 (19. d4 Kf7) 19… Kh7! 20. d4 g5 = ) 1-0.

Hornecker MT 2024 (2nd honorable mention)

File: Neuenschwander-2024-HorneckerMT.pgn

Theme: A white piece occupies a square X at least twice during the solution, then leaves it. These occupations must be done without capture and without check. The thematic piece may not be the white king.

The thematic square is a1. The solution of the study is easy although some precision is needed towards the end.

GBR: +0440.45e7a6 FEN: 7r/P1p1K2p/k2p4/5p2/B5p1/4P3/5PPb/6R1 w - - 0 1

1. Ra1! (theme) (1. Be8? Kxa7 2. Ra1+ Kb6 3. g3 h5 4. Rh1 h4 5. Rxh2 hxg3 6. Rg2 (6. Rxh8? g2) 6… Rh2 7. Rxg3 Rxf2 =) 1… Kxa7 (1… Be5 2. Be8+!) 2. g3 (2. Bd7+? Kb7 3. g3 h5 4. Rh1 h4 5. Rxh2 hxg3) 2… h5 3. Rh1 h4 4. Rxh2 hxg3 5. Rxh8 g2 6. Ra8+ Kb7 (6… Kb6 7. Rb8+) 7. Bc6+ Kxc6 8. Ra1! (theme) 8… Kd5 9. Rg1 Ke4 10. Rxg2 d5 11. Kf6 c5 (11… Kf3 12. Rh2 c5 13. Kxf5) 12. Rg1! Back to the square where the rook started the round trip (via the four corner squares) (12. Kg5? Kf3 13. Rh2 d4! 14. exd4 cxd4 15. Kxf5 d3 16. Ke5 d2 17. Rh1 Kxf2 =) (12. Rg3? c4 13. Kg5 c3 14. Rg1 g3! 15. Rxg3 (15. fxg3 Kxe3 16. Kxf5 c2 17. Rc1 Kd2 18. Rh1 Ke3! 19. Rc1 Kd2 20. Ra1 Ke3!) 15… c2 16. Rg1 f4! 17. exf4 d4) 1-0.

1. Kg2 Bb6! Prepares the defence of the h-pawn. (1… Ke4 2. Nb3! Bb4 ( 2… Bb6 3. Nd2+ = (3. Kxh2? Kd3) ) 3. Kxh2 =) (1… Ke4) 2. Nb3! ( After 2. Kxh2? , the white knight cannot be saved. 2… Ke4 3. Nc2 Ba5 4. Na3 Kd3 5. Kg2 Bb4 6. Nb5 Kc4 7. Nc7 (7. Na7 Bxd6 8. Nc8 Bc5 -+) 7… Bxd6 8. Ne8 Be5 -+) 2… Bg1 3. Nc1! (3. Na5? Ke5 4. Nb7 Kd5 -+) 3… Ke5 4. Na2! Ke6! Sets up a trap. 5. Kh1! (5. Nb4? is premature because of 5… Bc5! -+) 5… Kxd6 6. Nb4! Ke6 (6… Kc5 7. Na6+! Kc4 8. Nb8! ( 8. Nc7 Bd4 -+) 8… d5 9. Nd7 d4 10. Ne5+ =) 7. Na6! (7. Kg2? Bc5 -+) 7… Bd4! (7… Kd5 8. Nb8 d6 9. Nd7 =) 8. Kg2! (8. Kxh2? Be5+! 9. Kg2 Bd6! -+) 8… Kd5 9. Nb8! d6 10. Kxh2 Finally. 10… Ba7 11. Na6! (11. Nd7? Ke6 12. Nf8+ Kf7 =) 1/2-1/2.

Study no. 31 (Table 1)

The cook can easily be avoided by placing the black rook on f5. Note that the minor dual on move 2 could also be avoided with the black rook on f7 in the starting position. However, this would remove some content.
